The paper discusses the use of agent-based modeling and genetic programming to understand the decision-making process of the ancestral Pueblo in their agricultural practices. This involves exploring the importance of causal factors that affect individual behavior, which falls under the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and social and information networks (cs.SI). The use of genetic programming and random forest regression to evaluate the importance of these factors falls under computational engineering (cs.CE) and machine learning (cs.MA). Finally, the study focuses on the socio-agricultural behavior of the ancestral Pueblo, which falls under the category of social and information networks (cs.SOC).
